ound-Randy-paper/dp/B07FZ99HXL|title=Travis Scott \u2013 ASTROWORLD [Vinyl]|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=August 4, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Travis Scott}}\n\n[[Category:2018 albums]]\n[[Category:Travis Scott albums]]\n[[Category:Grand Hustle Records albums]]\n[[Category:Epic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Mike Dean (record producer)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Travis Scott]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Cardo]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by FKi (production team)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Frank Dukes]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Hit-Boy]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Thundercat]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Kevin Parker]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Murda Beatz]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Nineteen85]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Sonny Digital]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by WondaGurl]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Cubeatz]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Tay Keith]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Allen Ritter]]\n[[Category:Cactus Jack Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|ASTROWORLD|the theme park|Six Flags AstroWorld}}\n{{short description|2018 studio album by Travis Scott}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name               = Astroworld\n| type               = studio\n| artist             = [[Travis Scott]]\n| cover              = Astroworld by Travis Scott.jpg\n| alt                = \n| released           = {{Start date|2018|08|03}}\n| recorded           = 2016 \u2013 July 2018\n| studio             = \n* Cactus (Honolulu, Hawaii)\n* [[Chalice Recording Studios|Chalice]] and [[Westlake Recording Studios|Westlake]] (Los Angeles, California)\n* [[Conway Recording Studios|Conway]] and [[Henson Recording Studios|Henson]] (Hollywood, California)\n* Dean's List House of Hits ([[Cypress, Texas]])\n* Studio 713 (Houston, Texas)\n| genre              = <!--Genres need to be sourced. Aim for generality and no more than four genres per [[Template:Infobox musical artist/doc#genre]]-->[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]<ref name=\"Pitchfork\" />\n| length             = {{Duration|m=58|s=33}}\n| label              = \n* [[Cactus Jack Records|Cactus Jack]]\n* [[Grand Hustle Records|Grand Hustle]]\n* [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer           =\n* [[30 Roc]]\n* B Wheezy\n* [[Bkorn]]\n* [[Cardo (record producer)|Cardo]]\n* [[Cubeatz]]\n* [[FKi 1st]]\n* [[Frank Dukes]]\n* [[Hit-Boy]]\n* [[J Beatzz]]\n* [[June James (record producer)|June James]]\n* [[Mike Dean (record producer)|Mike Dean]]\n* [[Murda Beatz]]\n* [[Nineteen85]]\n* [[OZ (record producer)|OZ]]\n* [[Rog\u00e9t Chahayed]]\n* [[Sevn Thomas]]\n* [[Sonny Digital]]\n* [[Tame Impala]]\n* [[Tay Keith]]\n* [[Thundercat (musician)|Thundercat]]\n* [[TM88]]\n* Travis Scott\n* Wallis Lane\n* [[WondaGurl]]\n| prev_title         = [[Huncho Jack, Jack Huncho]]\n| prev_year          = 2017\n| next_title         = [[JackBoys]]\n| next_year          = 2019\n| misc               = {{Extra album cover\n| header = Alternative cover\n| type = studio\n| cover = Astroworld alt cover.jpg\n| caption = \"Night\" version cover.\n}}{{Singles\n| name = Astroworld\n| type = studio\n| single1 = [[Butterfly Effect (Travis Scott song)|Butterfly Effect]]\n| single1date = May 15, 2017\n| single2 = [[Sicko Mode]]\n| single2date = August 21, 2018\n| single3 = [[Yosemite (song)|Yosemite]]\n| single3date = November 20, 2018\n| single4 = [[Wake Up (Travis Scott song)|Wake Up]]\n| single4date = March 26, 2019\n}}\n}}\n'''''Astroworld''''' is the third studio album by American rapper and record producer [[Travis Scott]]. It was released on August 3, 2018, through [[Cactus Jack Records]] and [[Grand Hustle Records]], and distributed by [[Epic Records]]. The album follows his second studio album ''[[Birds in the Trap Sing McKnight]]'' (2016), and his collaborative album ''[[Huncho Jack, Jack Huncho]]'' (2017) with [[Quavo]]. \n\nThe album features guest vocals from [[Kid Cudi]], [[Frank Ocean]], [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], [[The Weeknd]], [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]], [[Philip Bailey]], [[21 Savage]], [[Swae Lee]], [[Gunna (rapper)|Gunna]], [[Nav (rapper)|Nav]], [[Quavo]], [[Takeoff (rapper)|Takeoff]], [[Juice Wrld]], [[Sheck Wes]], and [[Don Toliver]], among others. Production was handled by multiple producers, including [[Mike Dean (record producer)|Mike Dean]], [[Allen Ritter]], [[Hit-Boy]], [[WondaGurl]], [[Tay Keith]], [[Tame Impala]], [[Frank Dukes]], [[Sonny Digital]], and [[Thundercat (musician)|Thundercat]].\n\nThe album title is named after the defunct theme park [[Six Flags AstroWorld]], which was located in [[Houston]], [[Texas]] prior to its closure. Scott aimed for the album to sound like \"taking an amusement park away from kids.\" He also described the album as a continuation of his debut album ''[[Rodeo (Travis Scott album)|Rodeo]]'' (2015). ''Astroworld'' is a [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] album, incorporating elements of [[Trap music|trap]] and [[psychedelic music]]. The album was supported by four singles, \"[[Butterfly Effect (Travis Scott song)|Butterfly Effect]]\", \"[[Sicko Mode]]\", \"[[Yosemite (song)|Yosemite]]\", and \"[[Wake Up (Travis Scott song)|Wake Up]]\". \n\n''Astroworld'' received widespread acclaim and performed well commercially, debuting atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with 537,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s, of which 270,000 were pure sales. It was certified [[RIAA certification|triple platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). It was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Album|Best Rap Album]] at the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards|2019 Grammy Awards]], while \"Sicko Mode\" received nominations for [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Performance|Best Rap Performance]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Song|Best Rap Song]]. The album was named one of the best albums of 2018 and the decade by several publications.\n\n== Background ==\nThe title of the album was announced in May 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/05/travis-scott-announces-astroworld/|title=Travis Scott Announces 'Astroworld' Album|work=XXL|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=July 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712155826/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/05/travis-scott-announces-astroworld/|archive-date=July 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.38837/title.travi-scott-announces-astroworld-album|title=Travi$ Scott Announces \"ASTROWORLD\" Album|work=HipHopDX|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=July 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730202843/https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.38837/title.travi-scott-announces-astroworld-album|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2016/05/17/travis-scott-announces-third-album-astroworld/|title=Travis Scott Announces Third Album 'Astroworld'|work=Rap-Up|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=July 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721024750/http://www.rap-up.com/2016/05/17/travis-scott-announces-third-album-astroworld/|archive-date=July 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and initially teased for a 2017 release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2016/12/travis-scott-announces-astroworld|title=Travis Scott Announces 'Astroworld' Project and Tour for 2017|work=Highsnobiety|date=December 31, 2016|accessdate=July 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140558/https://hypebeast.com/2016/12/travis-scott-announces-astroworld|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The album title is named after the defunct theme park [[Six Flags AstroWorld]], which was located in [[Houston]], [[Texas]] prior to its closure in 2005. In a 2017 interview with ''[[GQ]]'', Scott spoke on the title of the album: \"They tore down AstroWorld to build more apartment space. That's what it's going to sound like, like taking an amusement park away from kids. We want it back. We want the building back. That's why I'm doing it. It took the fun out of the city.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/travis-scott-gq-style-spring-summer-2017|title=Travis Scott doesn't fall on stage, he flies|work=GQ|date=March 14, 2017|accessdate=July 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713171451/http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/travis-scott-gq-style-spring-summer-2017|archive-date=July 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Scott described the album as a continuation of his debut album, ''[[Rodeo (Travis Scott album)|Rodeo]]'' (2015), stating: \"My whole idea was, if you locked into ''Rodeo'', you definitely locked into ''Astroworld''. I'm just finishing the saga I started on my first album. This is supposed to be my second album. I had to go quick, because like I said, I had all these ideas, I just had to get off real quick, but now I'm finally back home with ''Astroworld''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/travis-scotts-wav-radio-show-to-air-after-astroworld-release-news.56440.html|title=Travis Scott's .wav Radio Show To Air After \"Astroworld\" Release|work=HotNewHipHop|date=August 2, 2018|accessdate=August 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802203640/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/travis-scotts-wav-radio-show-to-air-after-astroworld-release-news.56440.html|archive-date=August 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Recording ==\nRecording for the album took place between 2016 and 2018, with Travis Scott posting updates through social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/12/travis-scott-astroworld-drop-in-2017/|title=Travis Scott Says 'Astroworld' LP Will Drop in 2017|work=XXL|date=December 31, 2016|accessdate=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731062124/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/12/travis-scott-astroworld-drop-in-2017/|archive-date=July 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/travis-scott-says-hes-locked-in-working-on-astroworld-news.45187.html|title=Travis Scott Says He's \"Locked In\" Working On \"AstroWorld\"|work=HotNewHipHop|date=March 6, 2018|accessdate=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731062254/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/travis-scott-says-hes-locked-in-working-on-astroworld-news.45187.html|archive-date=July 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2018/01/06/travis-scotts-astroworld-slated-released-first-quarter-2018/|title=Travis Scott's 'Astroworld' Is Slated to be Released in the First Quarter of 2018|work=The Source|date=January 6, 2018|accessdate=July 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712154727/http://thesource.com/2018/01/06/travis-scotts-astroworld-slated-released-first-quarter-2018/|archive-date=July 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2018, it was reported that Scott was completing the album in Hawaii with a variety of recording artists and producers, such as [[Mike Dean (record producer)|Mike Dean]], [[Nav (rapper)|Nav]], [[Frank Dukes]], [[Sonny Digital]], [[WondaGurl]], [[Sheck Wes]], [[Gunna (rapper)|Gunna]], [[Wheezy (record producer)|Wheezy]], [[Don Toliver]], [[Allen Ritter]] and [[Amir Esmailian|Amir \"Cash\" Esmailian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/07/travis-scott-heads-to-hawaii-mike-dean-nav-to-finish-astroworld-album/|title=Travis Scott Heads to Hawaii to Finish 'Astroworld' Album|work=XXL|date=July 13, 2018|accessdate=July 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713152919/http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/07/travis-scott-heads-to-hawaii-mike-dean-nav-to-finish-astroworld-album/|archive-date=July 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/07/travis-scott-assembles-supergroup-of-artists-and-producers-in-hawaii-to-finish-astroworld|title=Travis Scott Assembles Supergroup of Artists and Producers in Hawaii to Finish 'AstroWorld'|work=Complex|date=July 12, 2018|accessdate=July 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712205326/https://www.complex.com/music/2018/07/travis-scott-assembles-supergroup-of-artists-and-producers-in-hawaii-to-finish-astroworld|archive-date=July 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.power106.com/2018/07/12/rumors-are-circling-that-travis-scotts-album-astroworld-is-complete/|title=Rumors are Circling that Travis Scott's Album \"AstroWorld\" is Complete|publisher=Power 106|date=July 12, 2018|accessdate=July 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713093045/http://www.power106.com/2018/07/12/rumors-are-circling-that-travis-scotts-album-astroworld-is-complete/|archive-date=July 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n{{Listen\n| pos = right\n| filename = Stargazing.ogg\n| title = \"Stargazing\"\n| description = On \"Stargazing\", Travis Scott discusses embracing success, which allows him to shed the horrors of his upbringing and leave behind habits such [[Purple drank|drug abuse]] to assume a position as a role model and become a better man. The brooding, [[psychedelic music|psychedelic]] track is built on [[Trap music|trap]] beats, glistening notes and eerie cooing.\n| format = [[Ogg]]\n| filename2 = Stop Trying to Be God.ogg\n| title2 = \"Stop Trying to Be God\"\n| description2 = The ethereal composition weaves together heavenly hums and wistful [[harmonica]] lines. Scott's lyrics focuses on rebuking those whose egos make them feel and act [[God complex|god-like]].\n| format2 = [[Ogg]]\n}}\n\n''Astroworld'' is a [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] album, incorporating elements of [[Trap music|trap]] and [[psychedelic music]].<ref name=\"Pitchfork\" /><ref name=\"COS\" /><ref name=\"EW\" /> \"Stargazing\" has been described as a \"psychedelic trap\" song,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/travis-scott-stargazing/|title=\"Stargazing\" by Travis Scott Review|work=Pitchfork|date=August 4, 2018|accessdate=August 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809062736/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/travis-scott-stargazing/|archive-date=August 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> while \"Coffee Bean\" is said to inhabit \"[[Old-school hip hop|old school hip hop]] territory with a blissed-out funk guitar.\"<ref name=\"The Independent\" /> The song \"Skeletons\" has been labelled as \"kaleidoscope-pop\" by ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' that draws lyrical influences from [[Kanye West]].<ref name=\"Pitchfork\" />\n\n== Artwork ==\nThe cover was shot by American photographer [[David LaChapelle]], and features a giant golden [[inflatable]] of Scott's head as the entrance to an amusement park, with children, parents, and park employees in front of it. A second cover features the same amusement park entrance at nighttime, replacing the family-friendly features with adult-themed content.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/travis-scott-reveals-cover-for-new-album-astroworld/|title=Travis Scott Reveals 2 Covers for New Album ''Astroworld''|work=Pitchfork|date=July 31, 2018|accessdate=August 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731233420/https://pitchfork.com/news/travis-scott-reveals-cover-for-new-album-astroworld/|archive-date=July 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/travis-scott-shares-a-second-album-cover-for-astroworld-news.56297.html|title=Travis Scott Shares A Second Album Cover For \"Astroworld\"|work=HotNewHipHop|date=August 1, 2018|accessdate=August 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801061208/https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/travis-scott-shares-a-second-album-cover-for-astroworld-news.56297.html|archive-date=August 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On August 1, 2018, transgender model [[Amanda Lepore]], who is a known collaborator with LaChapelle, questioned why she had been excluded on the final version of the second cover.<ref name=\"Lepore\">{{cite web |last=Tanzer |first=Myles |title=Amanda Lepore removed from Travis Scott's Astroworld album cover |url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/08/01/amanda-lepore-travis-scott-astroworld-album-cover |website=The Fader |accessdate=August 2, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802024414/http://www.thefader.com/2018/08/01/amanda-lepore-travis-scott-astroworld-album-cover |archive-date=August 2, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> LaChapelle later responded, stating that it was due to Lepore upstaging the other models on the cover.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/style/2018/08/david-lachapelle-explains-why-amanda-lepore-was-taken-off-travis-scott-astroworld-cover|title=David LaChapelle Explains Why Amanda Lepore Was Taken Off Travis Scott's 'ASTROWORLD' Cover|last=Cowen|first=Trace William|work=Complex|date=August 2, 2018|accessdate=August 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807033412/https://www.complex.com/style/2018/08/david-lachapelle-explains-why-amanda-lepore-was-taken-off-travis-scott-astroworld-cover|archive-date=August 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Travis Scott would also respond via [[Twitter]], explaining he had \"nothing but respect for the LGBTQ community.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8468674/travis-scott-amanda-lepore-trans-model-album-art-removal|title=Travis Scott Responds to Trans Model's Removal From Album Art: 'I Have Nothing but Respect for the LGBTQ Community'|website=Billboard|last=Crowley|first=Patrick|date=August 4, 2018|accessdate=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, [[TMZ]] reported that featured artist [[Frank Ocean]] filed a cease and desist against Scott to have his verse on \"Carousel\" removed due to disagreements over the song's sound.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8475232/frank-ocean-travis-scott-carousel-astroworld-cease-and-desist|title=Frank Ocean Files Cease & Desist to Have Vocals Taken Off Travis Scott's 'Astroworld': Report|work=Billboard|last=Saponara|first=Michael|date=September 14, 2018|accessdate=June 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701032724/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8475232/frank-ocean-travis-scott-carousel-astroworld-cease-and-desist|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Ocean soon issued a clarification, stating: \"I think the song sounds cool [...] I also approved it before it came out so the cease and desist wasn't about \ud83d\udd0a it was {{nowrap|about \ud83c\udff3\ufe0f&zwj;\ud83c\udf08.}} Me and Travis resolved it amongst ourselves weeks ago. \ud83d\udc96\" Ocean's use of the [[pride flag]] was seen to be a reference to the controversial removal of Lepore from the cover.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kiefer|first=Halle|url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/09/frank-ocean-astroworld-cease-and-desist-resolved-weeks-ago.html|title=Frank Ocean Says His Astroworld Cease and Desist, Resolved 'Weeks Ago,' Was Never About The Music|work=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]|date=September 14, 2018|accessdate=September 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915052930/http://www.vulture.com/2018/09/frank-ocean-astroworld-cease-and-desist-resolved-weeks-ago.html|archive-date=September 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Release and promotion ==\nIn May 2017, Scott uploaded three songs to [[SoundCloud]]\u2014\"A Man\", \"Green and Purple\" featuring [[Playboi Carti]], and \"[[Butterfly Effect (Travis Scott song)|Butterfly Effect]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/73552-travis-scott-drops-3-new-songs-listen/|title=Travis Scott Drops 3 New Songs: Listen|work=Pitchfork|date=May 16, 2017|accessdate=July 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730203250/https://pitchfork.com/news/73552-travis-scott-drops-3-new-songs-listen/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Butterfly Effect\" was released on May 15, 2017, for streaming and digital download as the album's lead single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/butterfly-effect-single/1238460728|title=Butterfly Effect \u2013 Single by Travis Scott on Apple Music|publisher=iTunes Store|accessdate=July 15, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180804030951/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/butterfly-effect-single/1238460728|archivedate=August 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It peaked at number 50 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"Hot 100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Travis-Scott/chart-history/hot-100|title=Travis Scott Chart History: Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=September 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926140845/https://www.billboard.com/music/Travis-Scott/chart-history/hot-100|archive-date=September 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The single, \"[[Watch (song)|Watch]]\" featuring [[Kanye West]] and [[Lil Uzi Vert]], was released on May 4, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/watch-feat-lil-uzi-vert-kanye-west-single/1378730785|title=Watch (feat. Lil Uzi Vert & Kanye West) \u2013 Single by Travis Scott on Apple Music|publisher=iTunes Store|accessdate=July 15, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180804031648/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/watch-feat-lil-uzi-vert-kanye-west-single/1378730785|archivedate=August 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The song peaked at number 16 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"Hot 100\" />\n\nOn July 27, 2018, a giant sculpture of Scott's head appeared on top of an [[Amoeba Music]] store in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.47822/title.giant-travis-scott-head-on-amoeba-hollywood-stokes-astroworld-hype|title=Giant Travis Scott Head on Amoeba Hollywood Stokes \"Astroworld\" Hype|work=HipHopDX|date=July 27, 2018|accessdate=July 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727232756/https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.47822/title.giant-travis-scott-head-on-amoeba-hollywood-stokes-astroworld-hype|archive-date=July 27, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/07/27/travis-scott-head-amoeba-records|title=Giant Travis Scott head appears over Amoeba Records in L.A.|work=The Fader|date=July 27, 2018|accessdate=July 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728110351/http://www.thefader.com/2018/07/27/travis-scott-head-amoeba-records|archive-date=July 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Multiple copies of the sculpture appeared in various other locations, including Scott's hometown of Houston, Texas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/giant-golden-travis-scott-head-appears-over-los-angeles-amoeba-records/|title=Giant Golden Travis Scott Head Appears Over Los Angeles' Amoeba Records|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|date=July 27, 2018|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730140512/https://pitchfork.com/news/giant-golden-travis-scott-head-appears-over-los-angeles-amoeba-records/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/07/30/giant-travis-scott-houston-astros|title=Second giant Travis Scott head pops up in Houston|last=Renshaw|first=David|date=July 30, 2018|work=[[The Fader]]|accessdate=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730170713/http://www.thefader.com/2018/07/30/giant-travis-scott-houston-astros|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> After significant internet speculation, the release date for ''Astroworld'' was announced on July 30, 2018, through social media, alongside an album trailer, which featured the track \"Stargazing\".<ref name=\"Release\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/travis-scott-confirms-new-album-astroworld-out-this-week/|title=Travis Scott Confirms New Album ''Astroworld'' Out This Week|work=Pitchfork|date=July 30, 2018|accessdate=July 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730181306/https://pitchfork.com/news/travis-scott-confirms-new-album-astroworld-out-this-week/|archive-date=July 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/07/travis-scott-reveals-astroworld-release-date|title=Travis Scott Reveals Release Date for 'Astroworld'|work=Complex|date=July 30, 2018|accessdate=July 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe release was followed by an episode of ''Wav Radio'' on [[Beats 1]] with Chase B. Three songs were premiered that did not make the final track listing: \"Houdini\" featuring Playboi Carti, \"Zoom\" featuring [[Gunna (rapper)|Gunna]], and \"Part Time\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2018/08/03/travis-scott-coffee-bean-hands-half-rinsed-lyrics|title=Travis Scott shares unreleased songs on special .wav radio episode|work=The Fader|date=August 3, 2018|accessdate=August 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804014220/http://www.thefader.com/2018/08/03/travis-scott-coffee-bean-hands-half-rinsed-lyrics|archive-date=August 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A music video for the song \"Stop Trying to Be God\" was released on August 6, 2018, directed by [[Dave Meyers (director)|Dave Meyers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/watch-travis-scott-get-biblical-in-wild-stop-trying-to-be-god-video-707333/|title=Watch Travis Scott Get Biblical in Wild 'Stop Trying to Be God' Video|work=Rolling Stone|date=August 6, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807110955/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/watch-travis-scott-get-biblical-in-wild-stop-trying-to-be-god-video-707333/|archive-date=August 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Scott performed a medley of three songs at the [[2018 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/vma/8471315/travis-scott-performs-astroworld-medley-2018-vmas-video |title=Travis Scott Takes the 2018 MTV VMAs to Space With Intergalactic 'Astroworld' Medley: Watch |last=Gracie |first=Bianca |date=August 20, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=October 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025031312/https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/vma/8471315/travis-scott-performs-astroworld-medley-2018-vmas-video |archive-date=October 25, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n\"[[Sicko Mode]]\" was sent to [[rhythmic contemporary|rhythmic]] and [[urban contemporary]] radio on August 21, 2018, as the album's second single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|title=Top 40 Rhythmic Future Releases|publisher=All Access|accessdate=August 14, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814033605/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|archivedate=August 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases|title=Urban/UAC Future Releases|publisher=All Access|accessdate=August 21, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819153209/https://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases|archivedate=August 19, 2018}}</ref> It peaked at number one on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"Hot 100\" /> \"[[Yosemite (song)|Yosemite]]\" was sent to urban contemporary radio on November 20, 2018, as the album's third single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases|title=Urban/UAC Future Releases|publisher=All Access|accessdate=November 7, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108034138/https://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases|archivedate=November 8, 2018}}</ref> The album's fourth single, \"[[Wake Up (Travis Scott song)|Wake Up]]\", was sent to rhythmic contemporary radio on March 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|title=Top 40-Rhythmic Future Releases|publisher=All Access|accessdate=March 21, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321152551/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|archivedate=March 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 8.1/10<ref name=\"ADM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/9471/Travis-Scott-Astroworld.aspx|title=Astroworld by Travis Scott reviews|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=August 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807220323/http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/9471/Travis-Scott-Astroworld.aspx|archive-date=August 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| MC = 85/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/astroworld/travis-scott|title=Astroworld by Travis Scott Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=August 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809024345/http://www.metacritic.com/music/astroworld/travis-scott|archive-date=August 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|last=Kellman|first=Andy|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/astroworld-mw0003200623|title=Astroworld \u2013 Travis Scott|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823042141/https://www.allmusic.com/album/astroworld-mw0003200623|archive-date=August 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2Score = B<ref name=\"COS\">{{cite web|last=Graves|first=Wren|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/08/album-review-travis-scott-astroworld/|title=Travis Scott Leans on His Strengths on ASTROWORLD|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=August 6, 2018|accessdate=August 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806195106/https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/08/album-review-travis-scott-astroworld/|archive-date=August 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = B<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web|last=Josephs|first=Brian|url=http://ew.com/music/2018/08/06/travis-scott-astroworld-ew-review/|title=Travis Scott 'Astroworld': EW Review|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=August 6, 2018|accessdate=August 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807002104/http://ew.com/music/2018/08/06/travis-scott-astroworld-ew-review/|archive-date=August 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev4Score = 9/10<ref name=\"Exclaim\">{{cite web|last=Guagliardi|first=Kassandra|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/travis_scott-astroworld|title=Travis Scott: Astroworld|work=[[Exclaim!]]|date=August 6, 2018|accessdate=August 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806171144/http://exclaim.ca/music/article/travis_scott-astroworld|archive-date=August 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Independent\">{{cite web|last=O'Connor|first=Roisin|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/astroworld-album-review-travis-scott-features-rating-tracklist-songs-a8479931.html|title=Travis Scott, Astroworld album review: Lightyears ahead of his peers|work=[[The Independent]]|date=August 6, 2018|accessdate=August 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806184417/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/astroworld-album-review-travis-scott-features-rating-tracklist-songs-a8479931.html|archive-date=August 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|last=Bassett|first=Jordan|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/travis-scott-astroworld-review-2362950|title=Travis Scott \u2013 'Astroworld' review|work=[[NME]]|date=August 3, 2018|accessdate=December 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804050029/https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/travis-scott-astroworld-review|archive-date=August 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 7.8/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/travis-scott-astroworld/|title=Travis Scott: Astroworld Album Review|last=Fitzmaurice|first=Larry|date=August 7, 2018|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=August 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807155838/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/travis-scott-astroworld/|archive-date=August 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|last=Weingarten|first=Christopher R.|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/review-travis-scott-starts-living-up-to-his-ambitions-on-astroworld-707220/|title=Review: Travis Scott Starts Living Up to His Ambitions on 'Astroworld'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=August 7, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807190434/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/review-travis-scott-starts-living-up-to-his-ambitions-on-astroworld-707220/|archive-date=August 7, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"The Times\">{{cite web|last=Hodgkinson|first=Will|authorlink=Will Hodgkinson|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/pop-review-travis-scott-astroworld-lt5h7pz5l|title=Pop review: Travis Scott: Astroworld|work=[[The Times]]|date=August 10, 2018|accessdate=August 31, 2019|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810025729/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/pop-review-travis-scott-astroworld-lt5h7pz5l|archive-date=August 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]''\n| rev10Score = 4/5<ref name=\"XXL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/reviews/2018/08/travis-scott-astroworld-album-review/|title=Travis Scott's 'Astroworld' Is the Best Version of Travis Scott|last=Glaysher|first=Scott|date=August 7, 2018|website=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|accessdate=August 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808012142/http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/reviews/2018/08/travis-scott-astroworld-album-review/|archive-date=August 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n''Astroworld'' was met with widespread critical acclaim. At [[Metacritic]], the album received an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 85, based on 19 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\" /> Aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]] gave it 8.1 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.<ref name=\"ADM\"/>\n\nJordan Bassett of ''[[NME]]'' gave ''Astroworld'' a perfect rating, praising the album's guest appearances and noting \"Stop Trying to Be God\" as \"a record of extraordinary prowess\", while describing \"Coffee Bean\" as \"a moment that encapsulates the scope and ambition of ''Astroworld''.\" Bassett concluded: \"This is the sound of a musician who has worked to forge an entire world, an empire, around himself \u2013 we can peer in, but from afar, guessing at his motives and life behind the velvet rope.\"<ref name=\"NME\" /> With similar acclaim, Kassandra Guagliardi of ''[[Exclaim!]]'' concluded that ''Astroworld'' \"shows the evolution of Travis Scott as an artist and is his most refined, imaginative, and rage-worthy project yet.\"<ref name=\"Exclaim\" /> Roisin O'Connor of ''[[The Independent]]'' described ''Astroworld'' as \"a futuristic record with virtually flawless production, that lingers on the mind long after the final track\" and labelled it Scott's \"most career-defining work to date.\"<ref name=\"The Independent\" /> For ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'', Wren Graves wrote that ''Astroworld'' is \"an album full of infectious flows and atmospheric beats.\"<ref name=\"COS\" /> Thomas Hobbs of ''[[Highsnobiety]]'' stated that ''Astroworld'' \"will be remembered as the moment Travis Scott produced a piece of music worthy of the riots he is capable of inducing. It's a wildly entertaining circus ride. Travis Scott desperately needed a great album to justify the hype, and with ''Astroworld'', he just might have a classic.\"<ref name=\"Highsnobiety\">{{cite web|last=Hobbs|first=Thomas|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/travis-scott-astroworld-review/|title=Travis Scott Fully Lives Up to His Potential on 'Astroworld'|work=Highsnobiety|date=August 6, 2018|accessdate=August 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806161748/https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/travis-scott-astroworld-review/|archive-date=August 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Grant Rindner of ''[[The Line of Best Fit]]'' saying \"Scott could have easily made another distorted, debaucherous project like his previous two albums, but by emphasizing his vocal performances and finding the best middle ground he ever has with his bevy of superstar collaborators, he's made ''Astroworld'' a theme park worth revisiting whether you came in as a stan or a skeptic.\"<ref name=\"The Line of Best Fit\">{{cite web|last=Rindner|first=Grant|url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/reviews/albums/astroworld-travis-scott-album-review|title=Travis Scott \u2013 Astroworld|work=The Line of Best Fit|date=August 8, 2018|accessdate=August 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821071507/https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/reviews/albums/astroworld-travis-scott-album-review|archive-date=August 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nLarry Fitzmaurice of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' labelled ''Astroworld'' as Scott's strongest album to date, stating that \"his skill as a curator helps sculpt a sticky, humid, psychedelic world with dazzling production and odd pleasures at every turn\", although considered Scott to \"play ringmaster to his neon-decayed circus of sound rather than become the main attraction.\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork\" /> Andrew Barker of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said, \"At 17 tracks, ''Astroworld'' is not without filler\u2014the [[21 Savage]] feature \"NC-17\" is tiresomely sophomoric, while \"Can't Say\" and \"Houstonfornication\" never really take shape\u2014but rarely does the album feel lazy or uninspired.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Barker|first=Andrew|url=https://variety.com/2018/music/reviews/travis-scott-astroworld-review-1202897426/|title=Album Review: Travis Scott's 'Astroworld'|work=Variety|date=August 6, 2018|accessdate=August 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821062643/https://variety.com/2018/music/reviews/travis-scott-astroworld-review-1202897426/|archive-date=August 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> For ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Christopher R. Weingarten complimented the first half of the album, though considered the second half to be weaker in comparison: \"Unfortunately, Scott doesn't keep the envelope pushing up for the whole album: a seven-song stretch in the back end is vintage Travis with its zoned-out, hypnotic throb. However, the rest marks the most interesting music of his career, Scott no longer just looking the part of a brilliant artist, but sounding like it too.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\" />\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Publication\n! scope=\"col\"| List\n! scope=\"col\"| Rank\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[AllMusic]]\n| AllMusic Best of 2018\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/year-in-review/2018|title=AllMusic Best of 2018|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=December 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215223219/https://www.allmusic.com/year-in-review/2018|archive-date=December 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n| 50 Best Albums of 2018\n| {{center|7}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/8489227/best-albums-2018-staff-picks|title=50 Best Albums of 2018: Staff Picks|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=December 10, 2018|accessdate=December 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213171709/https://www.billboard.com/photos/8489227/best-albums-2018-staff-picks|archive-date=December 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| 100 Best Albums of the 2010s\n| {{center|83}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8543722/best-albums-of-the-2010s-top-100|title=100 Best Albums of the 2010s: Staff Picks|work=Billboard|date=November 19, 2019|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]''\n| ''Clash'' Albums of the Year 2018\n| {{center|2}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/clash-albums-of-the-year-2018-10-1|title=Clash Albums of the Year 2018|work=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|date=December 19, 2018|accessdate=December 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219230451/https://www.clashmusic.com/features/clash-albums-of-the-year-2018-10-1|archive-date=December 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]''\n| 50 Best Albums of 2018\n| {{center|2}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/best-albums-2018/travis-scott-astroworld|title=50 Best Albums of 2018|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=December 5, 2018|accessdate=December 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206053319/https://www.complex.com/music/best-albums-2018/travis-scott-astroworld|archive-date=December 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| 20 Best Albums of 2018\n| {{center|20}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/music/2018/12/06/the-20-best-albums-of-2018/|title=20 Best Albums of 2018|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=December 6, 2018|accessdate=December 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206192623/https://ew.com/music/2018/12/06/the-20-best-albums-of-2018/|archive-date=December 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| Top 10 Hip-Hop Albums of 2018\n| {{center|6}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/exclaim_s_top_10_hip-hop_albums-best_of_2018/page/1|title=Exclaim!'s Top 10 Hip-Hop Albums|work=[[Exclaim!]]|date=December 10, 2018|accessdate=January 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112095015/https://exclaim.ca/musi